# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

In the pivotal SURPASS-1 trial, tirzepatide monotherapy at 5, 10, and 15 mg doses reduced HbA1c by −1.87%, −1.89%, and −2.07% from baseline, respectively, compared to a +0.04% change with placebo over 40 weeks.[1] When compared to basal insulin in SURPASS-3, tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg produced HbA1c reductions of −1.93%, −2.20%, and −2.37%, respectively, versus −1.34% with insulin degludec over 52 weeks.[1][2] In the higher cardiovascular risk population of SURPASS-4, tirzepatide doses led to reductions of −2.24%, −2.43%, and −2.58% versus −1.44% with insulin glargine.[1][3] In the Asia-Pacific SURPASS-AP-Combo trial, tirzepatide was superior to insulin glargine, with HbA1c reductions of −2.24%, −2.44%, and −2.49% for the 5, 10, and 15 mg doses, respectively, compared to −0.95%.[4] A post-hoc analysis of SURPASS-AP-Combo found that patients with a higher baseline HbA1c (>8.5%) experienced significantly greater HbA1c reductions with all tirzepatide doses compared to those with lower baseline HbA1c.[5] Tirzepatide also demonstrated rapid glycemic control, with a median time to achieve HbA1c <7.0% of 8.1 weeks across doses, which was faster than the 12.0 weeks for semaglutide 1 mg in SURPASS-2 and 12.1 weeks for insulin degludec in SURPASS-3.[6] For weight loss in type 2 diabetes, tirzepatide induced substantial reductions across the SURPASS program.[1] In SURPASS-1, body weight changes were −7.0 kg, −7.8 kg, and −9.5 kg for the 5, 10, and 15 mg doses, respectively, versus −0.7 kg with placebo.[1] In SURPASS-2, weight loss was −7.8 kg, −10.3 kg, and −12.4 kg with tirzepatide compared to −6.2 kg with semaglutide 1 mg.[1][7] In SURPASS-3, weight reductions were −7.5 kg, −10.7 kg, and −12.9 kg versus a +2.3 kg gain with insulin degludec.[1][2] In SURPASS-4, weight changes were −7.1 kg, −9.5 kg, and −11.7 kg with tirzepatide versus a +1.9 kg gain with insulin glargine.[1][3] A post-hoc analysis of SURPASS-AP-Combo showed that patients with higher baseline body weight (≥75 kg) experienced significantly greater absolute weight loss across all tirzepatide doses.[5] In SURPASS-2, the median time to first achieve ≥5% weight loss was faster with tirzepatide 5 mg (16.0 weeks) and 10/15 mg (12.4 weeks) than with semaglutide 1 mg (24.0 weeks).[6] A post-hoc analysis of SURMOUNT-2, a trial in patients with type 2 diabetes and obesity, found that the magnitude of placebo-corrected weight loss with tirzepatide 15 mg varied inversely with baseline HbA1c, with the greatest reduction (−17.7%) seen in the subgroup with HbA1c <7%.[8] In obesity trials without diabetes, weight loss was even more pronounced.[1] In SURMOUNT-1, the maximum tolerated dose of tirzepatide led to a mean weight reduction of −20.9% at 72 weeks versus −3.1% with placebo.[9]

### Safety

Gastrointestinal adverse events are the most common side effects of tirzepatide and are typically dose-dependent and mild to moderate in severity.[1][10] In the SURPASS-3 trial for type 2 diabetes, nausea was reported in 12-24% of tirzepatide-treated patients versus 2% with insulin degludec, vomiting in 6-10% versus 1%, and diarrhea in 15-22% versus 4%.[1][2] Similarly, in SURPASS-4, nausea occurred in 12-23% of tirzepatide patients versus 2% with insulin glargine, vomiting in 5-9% versus 2%, and diarrhea in 13-22% versus 4%.[1][3] The SURPASS J-mono trial in Japanese patients reported nausea in 12-20% with tirzepatide versus 8% with dulaglutide, vomiting in 5-12% versus 1%, and diarrhea in 9-17% versus 7%.[1][11] In obesity trials without diabetes, gastrointestinal events were also frequent; in SURMOUNT-4, during the open-label lead-in period, nausea was reported in 35.5% of participants, diarrhea in 21.1%, constipation in 20.7%, and vomiting in 16.3%.[12][13] During the subsequent double-blind period, gastrointestinal events remained more common with continued tirzepatide than placebo (diarrhea 10.7% vs 4.8%, nausea 8.1% vs 2.7%, vomiting 5.7% vs 1.2%).[12][13] The incidence of serious adverse events across trials is generally low and similar to comparators; for instance, in SURPASS-4, serious adverse event rates were 15-17% with tirzepatide versus 19% with insulin glargine, while in SURMOUNT-4, the rate was 3.0% in both the continued tirzepatide and placebo groups during the double-blind period.[1][13] Regarding thyroid cancer risk, animal studies have shown tirzepatide causes thyroid C-cell tumors in rats, leading to a boxed warning about the potential risk of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) in humans, and it is contraindicated in patients with a personal or family history of MTC or in patients with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2.[14] However, clinical trial data have not confirmed this human risk; the SURMOUNT-4 trial specifically reported no cases of medullary thyroid carcinoma or pancreatic cancer.[12][13] A real-world pharmacovigilance analysis of the FDA Adverse Event Reporting System (FAERS) detected a disproportionate reporting signal for medullary thyroid cancer with tirzepatide (ROR 13.67, 95% CI 4.35–42.96), though another similar analysis also noted the signal but found tirzepatide exhibited a similar risk of medullary thyroid cancer compared to GLP-1 receptor agonists.[15] A review article notes that pivotal outcome trials, including the SURPASS program, did not report clinically meaningful increases in autoimmune thyroid disease or sustained thyroid dysfunction.[16]

### Comparative

This trial also found tirzepatide superior for weight loss, with significantly greater reductions in body weight versus semaglutide 1 mg and higher proportions of patients achieving weight loss targets of ≥5%, ≥10%, and ≥15%.[7] Another aITC found all tirzepatide doses provided statistically significantly greater reductions in HbA1c and body weight compared to semaglutide 0.5 mg.[17] A post-hoc analysis of SURPASS-2 reported tirzepatide increased the odds of achieving stringent composite therapeutic targets (e.g., HbA1c <7% with weight loss >10%) compared to semaglutide 1 mg.[18] A systematic review and meta-analysis of direct comparative studies concluded tirzepatide was significantly superior to semaglutide for weight reduction, with a pooled standardized mean difference of 0.75 (95% CI: 0.52 to 0.92).[19] Model-based simulations suggest switching from stable maintenance doses of semaglutide or dulaglutide to tirzepatide can lead to further improvements in HbA1c and body weight.[20] A network meta-analysis in patients on basal insulin found tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg provided statistically significant, greater reductions in HbA1c and body weight versus GLP-1 RA comparators dulaglutide, exenatide, and lixisenatide.[21] The incidence of hypoglycemia (blood glucose <54 mg/dL) was low and comparable between groups.[7] An aITC reported comparable adverse event profiles between tirzepatide and semaglutide 0.5 mg, with no statistically significant differences in the odds of gastrointestinal AEs for any tirzepatide dose.[17] The network meta-analysis against other GLP-1 RAs found tirzepatide had a statistically significant higher likelihood of nausea versus placebo and exenatide 2 mg, but no significant difference versus dulaglutide, and no significant differences in treatment discontinuation due to adverse events.[21]

### Dose Response

Across the SURPASS phase 3 program in type 2 diabetes, tirzepatide demonstrates a clear dose-dependent relationship for improvements in both glycemic control and weight loss.[1] A systematic review and meta-analysis of RCTs concluded that within the 5–15 mg dose range, the effect of tirzepatide in lowering glycemia and reducing weight is dose-dependent, with the 15 mg dose achieving the best efficacy benefit.[22] For instance, in SURPASS-4 versus insulin glargine, the percentage of patients achieving ≥15% weight loss was 14%, 24%, and 37% for tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg, respectively, compared to <1%.[1] For HbA1c, the same analysis reported additional reductions of 0.20% (95% CI: -0.26 to -0.15) with 10 mg versus 5 mg, 0.30% (95% CI: -0.36 to -0.24) with 15 mg versus 5 mg, and 0.10% (95% CI: -0.16 to -0.04) with 15 mg versus 10 mg.[23] A pre-planned analysis of SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 found that while the median time to achieve HbA1c <7.0% was 8.1 weeks for all three tirzepatide doses, the time to reach HbA1c ≤6.5% was numerically faster with higher doses (12.1 weeks for all doses in the pooled analysis) compared to active comparators.[6] In SURPASS-2, the median time to first achieve ≥5% weight loss was 16.0 weeks with tirzepatide 5 mg and 12.4 weeks with the 10 and 15 mg doses, compared to 24.0 weeks with semaglutide 1 mg.[6] Subgroup analyses confirm this dose-dependent effect across different patient characteristics; for example, in the SURPASS-AP-Combo trial, greater reductions in HbA1c and body weight were consistently seen with higher tirzepatide doses regardless of baseline age, sex, BMI, or diabetes duration.[5] In SURMOUNT-2, placebo-corrected weight reduction with tirzepatide 15 mg varied by baseline HbA1c, but the dose-effect was clear within the trial, with the 15 mg dose producing greater weight loss than the 10 mg dose.[8][1] An indirect treatment comparison suggests tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg provide superior weight reduction versus semaglutide 2.4 mg in this population.[24]

### Population Subgroups

In older adults with type 2 diabetes, a post-hoc analysis of the pooled SURPASS-1 to -5 trials found that participants aged ≥65 years with a body mass index <30 kg/m² treated with tirzepatide experienced clinically meaningful HbA1c reductions of −1.97% to −2.10% across doses.[25] Another post-hoc analysis of all five SURPASS studies confirmed that reductions in HbA1c at week 40 or 52 were consistent for prespecified age subgroups (<65 and ≥65 years) compared with placebo or active comparators.[26] In that same trial, tirzepatide produced less weight loss at 52 weeks in patients with type 2 diabetes (−10.4%) compared to those without diabetes (−12.9%), though reductions in paracardiac fat and left ventricular mass were similar between groups.[27] For Asian patients, the phase 3 SURPASS-AP-Combo trial, conducted at 66 hospitals in China, South Korea, Australia, and India, demonstrated the efficacy of tirzepatide versus insulin glargine in a predominantly Chinese population (83.2% from China).[4] In that trial, all tirzepatide doses were superior to insulin glargine for HbA1c reduction at week 40, with least squares mean reductions of −2.24% (5 mg), −2.44% (10 mg), and −2.49% (15 mg) compared to −0.95% with glargine, and led to body weight reductions of −5.0 kg, −7.0 kg, and −7.2 kg, respectively, versus a gain of 1.5 kg with glargine.[4] A post-hoc subgroup analysis of SURPASS-AP-Combo found that reductions in HbA1c and body weight with tirzepatide were generally consistent across subgroups defined by age, sex, baseline HbA1c, BMI, body weight, diabetes duration, and concomitant oral medications, though a significantly greater HbA1c reduction was seen in younger patients (<65 years) with the 15 mg dose and in those with higher baseline body weight (≥75 kg) with the 10 mg dose.[5] In Japanese patients, the SURPASS J-mono trial demonstrated the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide monotherapy compared to dulaglutide, while the SURPASS J-combo trial evaluated tirzepatide as an add-on to a single oral antihyperglycemic medication.[11][28] Regarding cardiovascular risk, the SURPASS-CVOT trial in patients with type 2 diabetes and atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease found the primary composite endpoint of cardiovascular death, myocardial infarction, or stroke occurred in 12.2% of the tirzepatide group versus 13.1% of the dulaglutide group (hazard ratio 0.92), meeting non-inferiority.[29] Furthermore, in the SURPASS-SWITCH trial, which evaluated switching from dulaglutide to tirzepatide, the treatment effect for HbA1c and body weight reduction was consistent across baseline subgroups including age, sex, BMI, and HbA1c, with no significant treatment-by-subgroup interactions for most factors.[30]

### Limitations

Limitations: The corpus has significant gaps in its tier distribution, with only 19% of sources being T1 primary studies and 36% being T4 narrative reviews. The pipeline detected 13 high-severity contradictions, primarily concerning tirzepatide's effect on body weight and weight loss, where sources disagree substantially on the magnitude of the reported outcomes. The evidence horizon spans from 2010 to the present, but the heavy reliance on lower-tier evidence limits the robustness of the synthesized conclusions.

